bib_record.title: Properties of gamma-ray transitions in 56Co from 56Ni decay and 56Fe(p,n gamma)56Co

free_txt: Excitation functions for the first eight excited
states of 56Co were taken at 125 degrees in order to
minimize angular distribution effects.
Dead-time and amplifier pileup corrections, and
run-to-run normalizations.
A 2.5%-efficient Ge(Li) detector at
approximately 125 degrees from the beam direction and
at 5 cm from the target.
The errors arise from uncertainties in three
different quantities:
1) the y-ray peak areas,
2) the detector relative gamma-ray efficiency
corrections,
3) the run-to-run normalization.
Error values taken from the figure. For data without
given errors the errors are smaller than the data-point
symbols (about 6%).
The target was a 0.90-mg/cm2
iron foil.
Fig.8 (p.2392) in Phys.Rev.C,7,2379,1973 was
digitized by GSYS2.4.7.
Angular distributions of 56Co gamma rays has been
normalized to 1 at 90 degrees.
Least-squares fits to the experimental gamma-ray
angular distributions using the computer code GADFIT
were made; the even order Legendre polynomial
equation was used, the fitting parameters and mixing
ratio were defined.
Dead-time and amplifier pileup corrections, and
run-to-run normalizations.
A 2.5%-efficient Ge(Li) detector was rigidly
mounted on the goniometer arm with the face of
the detector 12.7 cm from the target. The detector
subtended approximately 10 degrees of arc.
The monitor of proton beam
The major uncertainties are in the gamma-ray
peak areas and the angle-to-angle normalizations.
A thin strip of iron foil measuring 1 mm by 10 mm
was carefully positioned on the axis of rotation of a
high angular precision goniometer.

The absolute normalization of the counting efficiency
curve was determined for the geometry used by counting
57Co, 137Cs, 54Mn, and 60Co intensity standards. The
precision quoted for the standards was +/-5%.
The neutron feeding to each state was determined from
the absolute gamma-ray intensities.
Dead-time and amplifier pileup corrections.
A 2.5%-efficient Ge(Li) detector was positioned
with its face 12.7 cm from the center of the target
and at 90 degrees to the beam.
No information on source of uncertainties
presented in the table.
Uncertainty in the target thickness (including
nonuniformities).
Uncertainty in the the integrated charge (+5%).
Uncertainty in the absolute normalization for
the efficiency curve (including uncertainty in
source positioning).
Uncertainty in the gamma-ray peak areas
The total error associated with the measurement is
approximately +/-15%.
The 56Fe foil was placed at 55 degrees with respect to
the beam direction. The 0.90+/-0.09-mg/cm2 target
thickness was determined by measuring the energy loss
of 5.48-MeV alpha particles from an 241Am source. The
target was placed 15 cm in front of the Faraday cup.
